The proposed syntax is<p><pre><code>  function f(val:any): val is SomeType {
    do checking and return boolean
  }
</code></pre>
and will be most likely available in 1.5.

If the generated JS were easier to read, js_of_ocaml would be very nearly perfect.  I think OCaml&#x27;s surface syntax is a bit ugly, but the semantics are great.<p>Particularly, I really like their solution to async programming.  I&#x27;m paraphrasing a bit, but it looks very nearly identical to an ordinary let ... in binding:<p><pre><code>    lwt result       = xhr &quot;http://example.com&quot; in
    lwt secondResult = xhr &quot;this url will be fetched after the first one completes&quot;
    and thirdResult  = xhr &quot;this url will be fetched in parallel with the second&quot;
    in (* use result, secondResult, and thirdResult here *)
</code></pre>
This desugars into a nested callback structure having the right shape.

